  "answer": "**Manu's cosmogonic treatment of *varṇa* in Chapter 1** begins after the sages request the *dharma* of the four *varṇas* (social orders):<sup>[1]</sup>\n\n> He, desiring to create the various kinds of progeny from his own body, first, through contemplation, created the waters, and in them he cast his seed. That seed became a golden egg [...]; in it he himself was born as Brahma [...]. And for the sake of the prosperity of the worlds, he caused the Brahmana, the Kshatriya, the Vaishya, and the Shudra to emanate from his mouth, arms, thighs, and feet.<sup>[2]</sup>\n\nThe chapter frames *varṇa* as emerging from the primordial creator's body during cosmic genesis (mouth → Brahmin; arms → Kshatriya; thighs → Vaiśya; feet → Śūdra), with duties assigned analogously later for \"the protection of this whole creation.\"<sup>[3]</sup>\n\n**Yājñavalkya's procedural opening in Chapter 1** responds to a parallel request from sages with no mythic preamble, directly listing the *varṇas* amid rules for sacraments (*saṃskāras*):\n\n> Having honored Yājñavalkya [...], the sages spoke: Declare to us in their entirety the *dharma* of the *varṇa*s [...]. Brāhmaṇa, Kṣatriya, Vaiśya, and Śūdra are the *varṇa*s; the first three are the twice-born. For them, the rites from conception to the funeral pyre are performed with sacred formulas.<sup>[4]</sup>\n\nDuties follow practically (e.g., \"The primary duty for a Kṣatriya is the protection of the people\"; Śūdra service to twice-born),<sup>[5]</sup> embedded in ritual and ethical procedures.\n\n**No genuine framework shift—prelude simply stripped.** Both uphold the same hierarchical *varṇa* order and duties (Brahmin primacy; Kshatriya protection; Vaiśya economic roles; Śūdra service), rooted in *smṛti* tradition. Manu narrates mythic origins for legitimacy; Yājñavalkya presumes them, prioritizing concise, applicable rules (e.g., *upanayana* timing by *varṇa*; conduct). This suits Yājñavalkya's pithy style, as a later *smṛti* distilling precedents like Manu without redundant cosmogony.\n\n[^1]: *Manusmṛti*, Ch. 1, [/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-b51d68](#).\n[^2]: *Manusmṛti*, Ch. 1, [/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-54fad8](#) (multi-para highlight via top-level `citation_url` from tool).\n[^3]: *Manusmṛti*, Ch. 1, [/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-f0b26c](#) (duties: Brahmin teaching/sacrifice; etc.).\n[^4]: *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, Ch. 1, [/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-97f0a4](#).\n[^5]: *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, Ch. 1, [/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-257298](#).",
